Tennis Kenya President James Kenani told Nation Sport that the success of the event will be used to gauge how the rest of the year will be for tennis considering that the players have a lot of compensating to do after a year that went to waste due to the Covid-19 pandemic.
"We are enthusiastic about starting the year on a high and it is our honor that we have been trusted to host this event by ITF. We intentionally used the last event of 2020 to get the players to warm up and get their heads back to competing and remind them that winning requires continuous practice regardless of their circumstances," he said.





Tennis Kenya had only four tournaments last year including the East African tennis championships, the BNP World Team Cup Africa Qualifiers, Davis Cup Euro/Africa Group 2 playoffs and the Tennis Kenya Senior and Junior Challenge series. The annual Kenya Open, Nairobi Open and Karen Open were cancelled due to the rise in the spread of the virus across the globe.
In the ITF World Juniors tourney girls category, Kenya will have top seed player Angela Okutoyi, currently ranked 271 in the ITF Junior rankings, her twin sister Roselida Asumwa, newcomer Debbie Akoth, Cynthia Wanjala and Shakira Varese.



